09187nam a2201237Ia 9783110988567DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20232023gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831109885677 a10.1515/97831109885672doi  a(DE-B1597)633998  a(OCoLC)1394872822  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aCOM0340002bisacsh04a004.019  aST 2782rvk0(DE-625)rvk/143644:00aPersonalized Human-Computer Interaction /ced. by Mirjam Augstein, Eelco Herder, Wolfgang Wörndl. 1aMünchen ;aWien : bDe Gruyter Oldenbourg, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (XIV, 362 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDe Gruyter Textbook00tFrontmatter -- tIntroduction -- tContents -- tList of Contributing Authors -- tPart I: Foundations of personalization -- t1 Theory-grounded user modeling for personalized HCI -- t2 User-centered recommender systems -- t3 Fairness of information access systems -- tPart II: User input and feedback -- t4 Personalization and user modeling for interaction processes -- t5 How to use socio-emotional signals for adaptive training -- t6 Explanations and user control in recommender systems -- t7 Feedback loops and mutual reinforcement in personalized interaction -- tPart III: Personalization purposes and goals -- t8 Personalizing the user interface for people with disabilities -- t9 Personalized persuasion for behavior change -- t10 Personalization approaches for remote collaborative interaction -- tPart IV: Personalization domains -- t11 Listener awareness in music recommender systems: directions and current trends -- t12 Tourist trip recommendations – foundations, state of the art and challenges -- t13 Pictures as a tool for matching tourist preferences with destinations -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPersonalized and adaptive systems employ user models to adapt content, services, interaction or navigation to individual users’ needs. User models can be inferred from implicitly observed information, such as the user’s interaction history or current location, or from explicitly entered information, such as user profile data or ratings. Applications of personalization include item recommendation, location-based services, learning assistance and the tailored selection of interaction modalities. With the transition from desktop computers to mobile devices and ubiquitous environments, the need for adapting to changing contexts is even more important. However, this also poses new challenges concerning privacy issues, user control, transparency, and explainability. In addition, user experience and other human factors are becoming increasingly important. This book describes foundations of user modeling, discusses user interaction as a basis for adaptivity, and showcases several personalization approaches in a variety of domains, including music recommendation, tourism, and accessible user interfaces.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aHuman-Machine-Interaction. 7aCOMPUTERS / Interactive & Multimedia.2bisacsh  aHuman-Computer Interaction.  aPersonalization.  aUser Models.  aUser-Centered Systems.1 aAbascal, Julio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArbelaitz, Olatz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAtzenbeck, Claus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAugstein, Mirjam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAugstein, Mirjam, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDietz, Linus W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerwerda, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb